{"user":"Bulk import me kuch files skip ho gaye.","assistant":"Title: Files skipped in bulk import\\nWhat's happening: Some files failed validation.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Check import log for skip reasons.\\n2) Common: Wrong format, encoding, missing columns.\\n3) Fix individual files → re-import.\\n4) Successful files still imported.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Workspace invite resend kaise karu?","assistant":"Title: Resend workspace invite\\nWhat's happening: Original invite expired/lost.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Workspace Settings → Members → Pending.\\n2) Find invite → Click 'Resend'.\\n3) Or delete old → send new invite.\\n4) Confirm correct email.\\nNew invite valid for 7 days.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Profit factor kaise improve karu?","assistant":"Title: Improve profit factor\\nWhat's happening: Gross profit vs gross loss ratio.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Increase average win (better exits).\\n2) Decrease average loss (tighter stops).\\n3) Filter bad trades (regime/time filters).\\n4) Improve win rate (better entries).\\nFormula: PF = Gross Profit / Gross Loss\\nTarget: > 1.5 for reliable strategies.\\nStatus: Strategy optimization"}
{"user":"Sharpe ratio negative hai kya karu?","assistant":"Title: Negative Sharpe ratio\\nWhat's happening: Returns worse than risk-free rate.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Check if strategy is actually losing.\\n2) Review entry/exit logic.\\n3) Add filters to avoid bad market conditions.\\n4) Reduce position size to lower volatility.\\nInterpretation: Negative Sharpe = strategy underperforming cash.\\nStatus: Strategy needs improvement"}
{"user":"Maximum drawdown zyada hai kaise reduce karu?","assistant":"Title: Reduce maximum drawdown\\nWhat's happening: Peak-to-trough too large.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Reduce position size (Half-Kelly).\\n2) Add stop loss if missing.\\n3) Use time-based exits.\\n4) Add regime filters (avoid bad markets).\\n5) Diversify across uncorrelated strategies.\\nTarget: Keep DD < 20% for psychological comfort.\\nStatus: Risk management"}
{"user":"Expectancy negative hai matlab?","assistant":"Title: Negative expectancy explained\\nWhat's happening: Long-term losing strategy.\\nFormula: E = (WinRate × AvgWin) - (LossRate × AvgLoss)\\nIf negative: More lost per trade than gained.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Improve win rate OR improve R:R.\\n2) Reduce losses with better stops.\\n3) Filter trades to take only best setups.\\n4) Consider strategy fundamentally flawed.\\nStatus: Strategy needs rework"}
{"user":"Win rate high but still losing money kyu?","assistant":"Title: High win rate but losing\\nWhat's happening: Wins too small, losses too big.\\nExample: 80% WR, ₹20 avg win, ₹100 avg loss\\nExpectancy: 0.8×20 - 0.2×100 = 16 - 20 = -₹4/trade\\nSolution:\\n1) Tighten stop losses.\\n2) Let winners run longer.\\n3) Improve R:R to at least 1:1.\\nKey insight: WR alone means nothing without R:R.\\nStatus: Common trap"}
{"user":"R:R ratio kya hona chahiye?","assistant":"Title: Ideal risk-reward ratio\\nWhat's happening: Balance between WR and R:R.\\nGuidelines:\\n- Scalping: 1:1 with 60%+ WR\\n- Day trading: 1.5:1 with 50%+ WR\\n- Swing: 2:1 with 40%+ WR\\n- Trend following: 3:1 with 30%+ WR\\nBreak-even formula: WR = 1/(1+R:R)\\nExample: 2:1 R:R needs 33% WR to break even.\\nStatus: Depends on style"}
{"user":"Recovery factor kya batata hai?","assistant":"Title: Recovery factor explained\\nWhat's happening: Profit relative to pain.\\nFormula: Net Profit / Max Drawdown\\nInterpretation:\\n- < 1: Not worth the risk\\n- 1-2: Marginal\\n- 2-5: Good\\n- > 5: Excellent\\nExample: ₹50K profit with ₹10K DD = RF of 5.\\nMeaning: Made 5x what you risked losing.\\nStatus: Risk-adjusted metric"}
{"user":"Calmar ratio kya hai?","assistant":"Title: Calmar ratio explained\\nWhat's happening: Annual return vs max drawdown.\\nFormula: CAGR / Max Drawdown\\nInterpretation:\\n- < 0.5: Poor\\n- 0.5-1.0: Acceptable\\n- 1.0-2.0: Good\\n- > 2.0: Excellent\\nUse: Long-term risk-adjusted performance.\\nSimilar to Sharpe but uses DD instead of volatility.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Sortino vs Sharpe me kya difference?","assistant":"Title: Sortino vs Sharpe\\nWhat's happening: Two risk-adjusted metrics.\\nSharpe: Uses total volatility (up + down)\\nSortino: Uses only downside volatility\\nDifference: Sortino doesn't penalize upside volatility.\\nPreference: Sortino better for asymmetric returns.\\nExample: Strategy with big wins, small losses → Better Sortino than Sharpe.\\nStatus: Both implemented"}
{"user":"VaR 95% matlab kya?","assistant":"Title: VaR 95% explained\\nWhat's happening: Value at Risk metric.\\nMeaning: 95% confidence daily loss won't exceed this.\\n5% of days may have bigger losses.\\nExample: VaR 95% = ₹10,000\\nInterpretation: On average, 1 in 20 days will lose > ₹10K.\\nUse: Set position limits, risk budgets.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"CVaR kya hai?","assistant":"Title: CVaR / Expected Shortfall\\nWhat's happening: Average loss beyond VaR.\\nFormula: Mean of losses exceeding VaR threshold.\\nExample: VaR 95% = ₹10K, CVaR = ₹15K\\nMeaning: When you do lose big, expect ₹15K avg.\\nUse: More conservative than VaR.\\nPreference: Better for fat-tailed distributions.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Beta negative matlab?","assistant":"Title: Negative beta explained\\nWhat's happening: Strategy moves opposite to market.\\nInterpretation:\\n- β = -1: Perfectly inverse\\n- β = -0.5: 50% inverse correlation\\nUse: Hedge against market drops.\\nExample: Short strategy during bull market.\\nPortfolio: Add negative beta for diversification.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Alpha positive chahiye kaise?","assistant":"Title: Achieve positive alpha\\nWhat's happening: Excess return beyond market.\\nFormula: α = Return - (Rf + β × (Rm - Rf))\\nTo improve:\\n1) Better entry/exit timing.\\n2) Unique edge not in market.\\n3) Lower correlation to benchmark.\\n4) Consistent outperformance.\\nPositive alpha = genuine skill/edge.\\nStatus: Strategy goal"}
{"user":"Genetic algorithm parameters kya set karu?","assistant":"Title: Genetic algorithm settings\\nWhat's happening: Evolution-based optimization.\\nRecommended settings:\\n- Population: 100 (50-200 range)\\n- Generations: 100 (50-500 range)\\n- Mutation rate: 0.15 (0.1-0.3)\\n- Crossover rate: 0.8 (0.7-0.9)\\n- Elite %: 5% (keep top performers)\\nLarger population = more exploration.\\nMore generations = better convergence.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"PSO vs Genetic kya use karu?","assistant":"Title: PSO vs Genetic Algorithm\\nWhat's happening: Two optimization methods.\\nGenetic: Good for discrete parameters.\\nPSO: Better for continuous parameters.\\nSpeed: PSO often faster convergence.\\nDiversity: GA maintains more variety.\\nRecommendation:\\n- Mixed params: Use Genetic\\n- All continuous: Try PSO first\\n- Large space: Either works\\nStatus: Both implemented"}
{"user":"Optimization heatmap me isolated peak dikha.","assistant":"Title: Isolated peak in heatmap\\nWhat's happening: Overfitting warning sign.\\nMeaning: Optimal parameters very sensitive.\\nSmall change = big performance drop.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Widen the search range.\\n2) Look for plateau regions instead.\\n3) Validate with Walk-Forward.\\n4) Simplify strategy (fewer params).\\nRobust strategies show wide colored regions.\\nStatus: Overfitting risk"}
{"user":"Walk-forward efficiency 0.3 hai.","assistant":"Title: Low walk-forward efficiency\\nWhat's happening: Severe overfitting detected.\\nEfficiency 0.3 = OOS only 30% of IS.\\nMeaning: Strategy falls apart on unseen data.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Reduce number of parameters.\\n2) Use simpler strategy logic.\\n3) Increase IS/OOS data.\\n4) Add robustness filters.\\nTarget: Efficiency 0.7-1.0.\\nStatus: Strategy needs simplification"}
{"user":"Monte Carlo worst case DD 50% dikha.","assistant":"Title: High Monte Carlo drawdown\\nWhat's happening: Trade order can cause 50% DD.\\nImplication: Current position sizing too aggressive.\\nNext actions:\\n1) If tolerance < 50%: Reduce size.\\n2) Formula: New Size = Current × (Tolerance/50%)\\n3) Example: 20% tolerance → reduce to 40% size.\\n4) Re-run Monte Carlo to verify.\\nKey: Prepare for worst case, not average.\\nStatus: Risk management"}
{"user":"Regime detection kaisa use karu?","assistant":"Title: Using regime detection\\nWhat's happening: Market phases identification.\\nRegimes detected:\\n- Trending Up (bullish)\\n- Trending Down (bearish)\\n- Ranging (sideways)\\n- High Volatility\\nUse case:\\n1) Enable strategy only in favorable regimes.\\n2) Adjust position size by regime.\\n3) Filter trades to matching conditions.\\nExample: Trend strategy → only Trending regimes.\\nStatus: Implemented (Premium)"}
{"user":"Correlation 0.9 hai do strategies me.","assistant":"Title: High strategy correlation\\nWhat's happening: Strategies move together.\\n0.9 = nearly identical behavior.\\nProblem: No diversification benefit.\\nNext actions:\\n1) Keep only better performing one.\\n2) Or modify one to be different.\\n3) Add uncorrelated strategy instead.\\n4) Recalculate portfolio weights.\\nTarget: Correlation < 0.3 for true diversification.\\nStatus: Portfolio warning"}
{"user":"Portfolio rebalancing kitni baar?","assistant":"Title: Rebalancing frequency\\nWhat's happening: Reset to target weights.\\nOptions:\\n- Monthly: Most common, moderate costs\\n- Quarterly: Lower costs, more drift\\n- Annually: Lowest cost, most drift\\nConsider:\\n1) Transaction costs\\n2) Drift tolerance\\n3) Market conditions\\nRecommendation: Quarterly with 5% drift threshold.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Equal weight vs optimized kya better?","assistant":"Title: Equal vs optimized weights\\nWhat's happening: Portfolio allocation choice.\\nEqual weight: Simple, robust, no optimization risk.\\nOptimized: Better Sharpe but fragile.\\nRecommendation:\\n1) Start with equal weight.\\n2) If > 5 strategies: Consider optimized.\\n3) Use risk parity as middle ground.\\n4) Rebalance periodically.\\nEqual weight often beats optimized out-of-sample.\\nStatus: Both available"}
{"user":"Risk parity kya hai?","assistant":"Title: Risk parity explained\\nWhat's happening: Equal risk contribution.\\nMethod: Weight inversely to volatility.\\nFormula: Weight ∝ 1/Volatility\\nBenefit: No single strategy dominates risk.\\nExample:\\n- Strategy A: 20% vol → Lower weight\\n- Strategy B: 10% vol → Higher weight\\nResult: Each contributes equal risk.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Efficient frontier kaise read karu?","assistant":"Title: Reading efficient frontier\\nWhat's happening: Optimal portfolio curve.\\nX-axis: Risk (volatility)\\nY-axis: Return\\nInterpretation:\\n- Points on curve: Optimal portfolios\\n- Above curve: Impossible\\n- Below curve: Suboptimal\\nChoice: Pick point matching your risk tolerance.\\nLeft side: Conservative (low risk, low return)\\nRight side: Aggressive (high risk, high return)\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Half Kelly kya hai?","assistant":"Title: Half Kelly explained\\nWhat's happening: Conservative Kelly sizing.\\nFull Kelly: Mathematically optimal for growth.\\nProblem: Very aggressive, high volatility.\\nHalf Kelly: Use f*/2 instead of f*.\\nBenefit:\\n1) 75% of growth rate\\n2) 50% of volatility\\n3) More stable equity curve\\n4) Psychological comfort\\nRecommendation: Always use Half-Kelly or less.\\nStatus: Implemented in calculator"}
{"user":"Optimal f kya hai?","assistant":"Title: Optimal f explained\\nWhat's happening: Empirical optimal fraction.\\nMethod: Based on actual trade history.\\nFormula: Fraction that maximizes geometric growth.\\nDifference from Kelly: Uses real trades, not theoretical.\\nProcess:\\n1) Test various fractions (5%, 10%, 15%...)\\n2) Calculate terminal wealth each\\n3) Find maximum growth point\\nCaution: Still aggressive, use fraction of optimal f.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Risk per trade 5% hai theek hai?","assistant":"Title: 5% risk per trade evaluation\\nWhat's happening: Position sizing assessment.\\nAnswer: TOO HIGH for most traders.\\nRisks:\\n- 10 consecutive losses = 50% DD\\n- RoR significantly increased\\n- Psychological pressure high\\nRecommendation:\\n- Conservative: 0.5-1%\\n- Moderate: 1-2%\\n- Aggressive: 2-3%\\n- Maximum: 5% (only with very high edge)\\nStart low, increase with proven edge.\\nStatus: Risk warning"}
{"user":"Stop loss kitna rakhna chahiye?","assistant":"Title: Stop loss guidelines\\nWhat's happening: Risk management decision.\\nMethods:\\n1) ATR-based: 1.5-3 × ATR\\n2) Structure: Below swing low/high\\n3) Percentage: 1-3% of entry\\n4) Volatility: 2 standard deviations\\nFactors:\\n- Timeframe: Larger TF = wider stops\\n- Asset: Volatile = wider stops\\n- Strategy: Trend = wider, Scalp = tight\\nBalance: Not too tight (whipsawed), not too wide (big losses).\\nStatus: Strategy dependent"}
{"user":"Trailing stop kaise set karu?","assistant":"Title: Trailing stop setup\\nWhat's happening: Lock in profits as price moves.\\nMethods:\\n1) Fixed pips: Trail by X pips\\n2) ATR-based: Trail by 2 × ATR\\n3) Percentage: Trail by X%\\n4) Parabolic SAR: Indicator-based\\nActivation: After X pips profit\\nTip: Don't trail too tight (noise exits).\\nRecommendation: 2-3 ATR trailing after 1.5 ATR profit.\\nStatus: Implemented in backtest"}
{"user":"Simulator me paths bahut different hain.","assistant":"Title: High variance in simulation paths\\nWhat's happening: Trade order significantly impacts results.\\nInterpretation: Strategy sensitive to sequence.\\nCauses:\\n1) Few total trades\\n2) Very large individual trades\\n3) Inconsistent edge\\nNext actions:\\n1) Increase trade count (more history).\\n2) Reduce position size.\\n3) Check for outsized trades.\\n4) Use median as realistic estimate.\\nStatus: Proceed with caution"}
