{"user":"EMA vs SMA kya difference hai?","assistant":"Title: EMA vs SMA\\nWhat's happening: Two moving average types.\\nSMA: Simple - equal weight to all periods.\\nEMA: Exponential - more weight to recent data.\\nDifferences:\\n- EMA reacts faster to price changes\\n- SMA smoother, less noise\\n- EMA better for short-term trading\\n- SMA better for long-term trends\\nFormula SMA: Sum(Close, N) / N\\nFormula EMA: Close × k + EMA_prev × (1-k), k = 2/(N+1)\\nStatus: Both in strategy templates"}
{"user":"MACD kaise interpret karu?","assistant":"Title: MACD interpretation\\nWhat's happening: Momentum + trend indicator.\\nComponents:\\n- MACD Line: EMA(12) - EMA(26)\\n- Signal Line: EMA(9) of MACD\\n- Histogram: MACD - Signal\\nSignals:\\n- Buy: MACD crosses above Signal\\n- Sell: MACD crosses below Signal\\n- Divergence: Price vs MACD direction differ\\nTip: Use with trend filter (EMA 200).\\nStatus: Available in scanner + strategies"}
{"user":"RSI divergence kya hota hai?","assistant":"Title: RSI divergence\\nWhat's happening: Price and RSI disagree.\\nBullish divergence: Price makes lower low, RSI makes higher low.\\n→ Potential reversal up.\\nBearish divergence: Price makes higher high, RSI makes lower high.\\n→ Potential reversal down.\\nStrength: Works best at extremes (< 30 or > 70).\\nCaution: Divergence can persist in strong trends.\\nUse in scanner: Add RSI + Price rules.\\nStatus: Pattern Recognition covers this"}
{"user":"Bollinger Band squeeze kya hai?","assistant":"Title: Bollinger Band squeeze\\nWhat's happening: Low volatility → breakout expected.\\nIdentification:\\n- Bands narrow significantly\\n- Band width at N-period low\\n- Volume typically decreases\\nTrade: Breakout direction unknown → wait for close outside band.\\nFilter: Volume confirmation on breakout.\\nTip: Squeeze often precedes big moves.\\nScanner rule: BandWidth < X + Volume spike.\\nStatus: Available in strategies"}
{"user":"ATR based stop loss kaise calculate karu?","assistant":"Title: ATR-based stop loss\\nWhat's happening: Volatility-adjusted stops.\\nFormula: Stop = Entry ± (Multiplier × ATR)\\nCommon multipliers:\\n- Tight: 1.5 × ATR\\n- Normal: 2.0 × ATR\\n- Wide: 3.0 × ATR\\nExample: Entry 100, ATR(14) = 5\\n- 2x ATR stop = 100 - 10 = 90 (long)\\nAdvantage: Adapts to market volatility.\\nCalculator: /calculators → ATR Stop Loss.\\nStatus: Implemented"}
{"user":"Backtest me margin call simulate hota hai?","assistant":"Title: Margin call simulation\\nWhat's happening: Account protection in backtest.\\nBehavior:\\n- If equity drops below required margin → positions closed\\n- Warning at 50% margin level\\n- Forced close at stop-out level\\nConfig: Backtest settings → Advanced → Margin model.\\nDefault: No margin call (unlimited margin).\\nRealistic: Enable margin modeling for accurate results.\\nStatus: Implemented (configurable)"}
